TY  - JOUR
T1  - Estimation of Market Power in a Nonrenewable Resource Industry
AU  - Ellis, Gregory M.
AU  - Halvorsen, Robert
Y1  - 2002/08/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/340777
DO  - 10.1086/340777
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 883
EP  - 899
VL  - 110
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In nonrenewable resource industries, the existence of a markup of price over marginal market cost may reflect the existence of an implicit user cost for the resource rather than market power. We show that valid estimates of market power can be obtained by the joint estimation of a restricted cost function and an inverse supply relation. Estimation of the model with data for the largest firm in the international nickel industry indicates that output price substantially exceeded marginal market cost, with most of the difference due to the exercise of market power rather than the user cost of the resource.
AB  - In nonrenewable resource industries, the existence of a markup of price over marginal market cost may reflect the existence of an implicit user cost for the resource rather than market power. We show that valid estimates of market power can be obtained by the joint estimation of a restricted cost function and an inverse supply relation. Estimation of the model with data for the largest firm in the international nickel industry indicates that output price substantially exceeded marginal market cost, with most of the difference due to the exercise of market power rather than the user cost of the resource.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/340777
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/340777
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Aging Population and the Size of the Welfare State
AU  - Razin, Assaf
AU  - Sadka, Efraim
AU  - Swagel, Phillip
Y1  - 2002/08/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/340780
DO  - 10.1086/340780
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 900
EP  - 918
VL  - 110
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Data for the United States and countries in western Europe indicate a negative correlation between the dependency ratio and labor tax rates and the generosity of social transfers, after other factors that influence the size of the welfare state are controlled for. This occurs despite the increased political clout of the dependent population implied by the aging of the population. This paper develops an overlapping generations model of intra? and intergenerational transfers (including old?age social security) and human capital formation that addresses this seeming puzzle. We show that with democratic voting, an increase in the dependency ratio can lead to lower taxes or less generous social transfers.
AB  - Data for the United States and countries in western Europe indicate a negative correlation between the dependency ratio and labor tax rates and the generosity of social transfers, after other factors that influence the size of the welfare state are controlled for. This occurs despite the increased political clout of the dependent population implied by the aging of the population. This paper develops an overlapping generations model of intra? and intergenerational transfers (including old?age social security) and human capital formation that addresses this seeming puzzle. We show that with democratic voting, an increase in the dependency ratio can lead to lower taxes or less generous social transfers.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/340780
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/340780
Y2  - 2024/03/19
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Lobbying Legislatures
AU  - Bennedsen, Morten
AU  - Feldmann, Sven E.
Y1  - 2002/08/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/340775
DO  - 10.1086/340775
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 919
EP  - 946
VL  - 110
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We analyze informational lobbying in the context of a multimember legislature that decides on the allocation of a public good. First, we observe that a majoritarian legislature provides widely different incentives for interest groups to lobby than a single decision maker does. Second, we compare a decentralized legislature, such as the U.S. Congress, to a parliament with strong party cohesion. Congress?s decentralized nature allows the strategic formation of policy coalitions among high?demand districts and the exclusion of low?demand districts. This increases the incentive to provide information about districts? demand relative to a legislature in which the governing coalition is fixed.
AB  - We analyze informational lobbying in the context of a multimember legislature that decides on the allocation of a public good. First, we observe that a majoritarian legislature provides widely different incentives for interest groups to lobby than a single decision maker does. Second, we compare a decentralized legislature, such as the U.S. Congress, to a parliament with strong party cohesion. Congress?s decentralized nature allows the strategic formation of policy coalitions among high?demand districts and the exclusion of low?demand districts. This increases the incentive to provide information about districts? demand relative to a legislature in which the governing coalition is fixed.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/340775
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/340775
Y2  - 2024/03/19
